    <h2>12. Where Old Debates Dissolve</h2>

    <p class="stub">
      <em>Forthcoming.</em> A surprising number of long-running
      &ldquo;this versus that&rdquo; debates do not need to be resolved
      under an observer-centric reading &mdash; they dissolve. Not because
      the questions are illegitimate, but because the framing rests on
      assumptions the framework no longer makes. Five to seven of the
      strongest dissolutions: materialism versus idealism (substrate is
      coherence, neither matter nor mind); reductionism versus holism
      (co-formed layers, neither reduces); determinism versus free will
      (a question of level, not metaphysics); realism versus anti-realism
      (relational invariants are real and observer-relative);
      objectivity versus subjectivity (no view from nowhere, but
      observer-relative objectivity is intact); locality versus
      nonlocality (network distance is not spatial distance); and
      &ldquo;why is there something rather than nothing&rdquo;
      (&ldquo;nothing&rdquo; is not a coherent alternative).
    </p>

    <h2>13. Where This Stands</h2>

    <p class="stub">
      <em>Forthcoming.</em> Honest accounting: how much of the framework
      stands on the axioms alone, what additional assumptions the rest
      requires, what would falsify the whole, and where an interested
      reader can find the underlying derivations. The framework offered
      as a contribution to a tradition, not a replacement for it. A
      return to the prologue&rsquo;s question.
    </p>

